  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Towards fulfillment of the right to a healthy environment for children and young people</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project will focus on providing opportunities for participation and training on environmental issues to children and teenagers from initially three poor neighbourhoods of Cartagena to enable the fulfilment of their right to a healthy environment and put fulfilment of this right into practice in their daily lives.

The Pastoral Action Team of the Archdiocese of Cartagena (SEPAS Cartagena) plan to work with a core group of 40 children and teenagers aged 8-19 years old from schools in these neighbourhoods, who come from high risk home situations.  These young people will also engage their peers and other community members.  The young environmental promoter group from the previous project (COL180) will play a role in training the new project participants, encouraging them to form a similar group for their own communities.  The project will carry out a participatory needs analysis of the issues in the communities at the beginning of the year and subsequent training will be adapted and tailored to this.

Some of the issues that the SEPAS Cartagena anticipate the young people will be able to address, with their support and training, are: improving the environment with the recovery of spaces currently used as dumping grounds, recycling, and better management of solid waste produced by people and animals.  The training on rights, including the right to a healthy environment will include how to hold local authorities to account and work with them to improve services.

One of the central concerns behind the SEPAS Cartagena&#x2019;s work with children and teenagers in this new project is to prevent them getting involved in violence, through gangs, drugs, sexual exploitation and trafficking which are all real problems in the three target communities.

To address these issues, the project will provide individual and group psychotherapy and psycho-social support, including the drawing up of life plans with the children and teenagers mapping their dreams and what they want to do with their lives.  There will also be a component of awareness raising training about drugs, trafficking and child sexual exploitation.  The 40 children and teenagers that they will work with most closely, will act as protagonists and young leaders, receiving training and then replicating it in their schools (four schools), with the support of their teachers and the SEPAS Cartagena.</narrative>
  </description>
